You can find the "deprecate" module on npm, the package manager for Node.js. To install it, run the following command in your terminal:


```
npm install deprecate
```
Once installed, you can use it in your project by requiring it and calling the `deprecate` function to wrap any deprecated code. Here's an example:


```javascript
var deprecate = require('deprecate');

var deprecatedFunction = deprecate(function() {
 // your deprecated code here
}, 'This function is deprecated and will be removed in the future');

deprecatedFunction();
```
This will log a message to the console each time the deprecated function is called, reminding you to update the code.

Here is an example of how to schedule a message to be sent to an SQS queue in TypeScript using the AWS SDK:


```
import * as AWS from 'aws-sdk';

const sqs = new AWS.SQS({ region: 'us-west-2' });

const params = {
 QueueUrl: 'https://sqs.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/123456789012/MyQueue',
 DelaySeconds: 60 * 60 * 5, // 5 hours
 MessageBody: 'Hello, world!'
};

sqs.sendMessage(params, (err, data) => {
 if (err) {
 console.error(err);
 } else {
 console.log(data);
 }
});
```
This example sends a message to the "MyQueue" SQS queue located in the "us-west-2" region with a delay of 5 hours, so the message will not be visible to consumers until 5 hours after the message is sent. The message body is "Hello, world!"

To change the schedule of the message, you can use the `changeMessageVisibility` method of the SQS client, passing the `ReceiptHandle` and the new `VisibilityTimeout` value in seconds


```
sqs.changeMessageVisibility({
 QueueUrl: 'https://sqs.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/123456789012/MyQueue',
 ReceiptHandle: data.ReceiptHandle,
 VisibilityTimeout: 60 * 60 * 6
 }, (err, data) => {
 if (err) {
 console.error(err);
 } else {
 console.log(data);
 }
});
```
This will change the visibility timeout of the message to 6 hours and will be visible to consumer in 6 hours after the message is sent.

Please note, this is a very basic example and you should consider adding error handling and other necessary configurations for production use.

The `ReceiptHandle` is a unique identifier for a specific message in an SQS queue. It is returned in the `sendMessage` response when a message is sent to the queue and can be used to perform actions on the message, such as changing its visibility timeout or deleting it.

In the example I provided earlier, when the message is sent to the queue using the `sqs.sendMessage` method, the response contains the `ReceiptHandle` of the message.


```
sqs.sendMessage(params, (err, data) => {
 if (err) {
 console.error(err);
 } else {
 console.log(data);
 }
});
```
The `data` object returned in the callback function of `sqs.sendMessage` contains the `ReceiptHandle` property, which is a string value that represents the unique identifier of the message in the queue.

So in the next function you can use `data.ReceiptHandle` as a reference to change the schedule of the message.


```
sqs.changeMessageVisibility({
 QueueUrl: 'https://sqs.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/123456789012/MyQueue',
 ReceiptHandle: data.ReceiptHandle,
 VisibilityTimeout: 60 * 60 * 6
 }, (err, data) => {
 if (err) {
 console.error(err);
 } else {
 console.log(data);
 }
});
```
This way you can change the schedule of the message using the `ReceiptHandle` that is obtained when the message is sent to the queue.

Yes, in your scenario, it sounds like the producer is the one who is changing the visibility timeout of the messages in the queue.

When a producer sends a message to the queue, it can set a `DelaySeconds` parameter which will cause the message to be invisible to consumers for a certain amount of time. The producer can then change the visibility timeout of the message later on, before it becomes visible to consumers, by using the `changeMessageVisibility` method and passing the `ReceiptHandle` of the message and the new `VisibilityTimeout` value in seconds.

For example, if the producer initially sets a delay of 5 hours, then after 4 hours the producer wants to change it to 6 hours, it can use the `changeMessageVisibility` method to change the visibility timeout to 6 hours:


```
sqs.changeMessageVisibility({
 QueueUrl: 'https://sqs.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/123456789012/MyQueue',
 ReceiptHandle: data.ReceiptHandle,
 VisibilityTimeout: 60 * 60 * 6
 }, (err, data) => {
 if (err) {
 console.error(err);
 } else {
 console.log(data);
 }
});
```
This way the message will become visible to consumers in 6 hours after the message is sent.

Keep in mind that the `ReceiptHandle` is not a permanent ID and it can be used only once, so you need to refresh the handle if you want to perform another action on the same message.
Also, as I mentioned earlier, SQS guarantees "at-least-once" delivery but not "exactly-once" delivery, meaning that a message may be delivered more than once to consumers, so you should implement additional logic (e.g. using a unique identifier for each message) to detect and discard duplicate messages.

