To dynamically allocate a new PostgreSQL database from Node.js, you can use a library like `pg` to interact with the PostgreSQL server. Here's an example of how you can create a new database:


```javascript
const { Client } = require('pg');

const client = new Client({
 host: 'localhost',
 user: 'postgres',
 password: 'password',
 port: 5432
});

client.connect();

client.query(`CREATE DATABASE new\_db`, (err, res) => {
 console.log(err ? err.stack : 'Database created successfully');
 client.end();
});
```
In this example, you connect to the PostgreSQL server using the `Client` constructor from the `pg` library, passing in the connection details such as the host, user, password, and port.

Once connected, you use the `query` method to execute a SQL query that creates a new database. If the operation was successful, the message "Database created successfully" will be logged, otherwise an error message will be logged.

Finally, the connection to the server is closed using the `end` method.

To dynamically allocate a new PostgreSQL cluster from Node.js, you can use a system-level call such as `exec` to run the `initdb` command and create the cluster. Here's an example of how you can create a new cluster:


```javascript
const { exec } = require('child\_process');

const cmd = `initdb -D /usr/local/pgsql/data`;

exec(cmd, (error, stdout, stderr) => {
 if (error) {
 console.error(`exec error: ${error}`);
 return;
 }

 console.log(`stdout: ${stdout}`);
 console.log(`stderr: ${stderr}`);
});
```
In this example, you use the `exec` method from the `child_process` module to run the `initdb` command, passing in the location where the cluster data should be stored.

The result of the command is captured in the `stdout` and `stderr` variables, which you can use to check for any errors or output. If an error occurs during the execution of the command, it will be logged using the `console.error` method.

Note: This is just an example, and the specific implementation details of creating a new PostgreSQL cluster may vary depending on your operating system and installation. You may also need to run the `initdb` command with superuser privileges.

Here's an example of parsing the output of the `initdb` command and saving it to Redis:


```javascript
const { exec } = require('child\_process');
const redis = require('redis');

const cmd = `initdb -D /usr/local/pgsql/data`;
const redisClient = redis.createClient();

exec(cmd, (error, stdout, stderr) => {
 if (error) {
 console.error(`exec error: ${error}`);
 return;
 }

 const output = `stdout: ${stdout}\nstderr: ${stderr}`;
 redisClient.set('initdb\_output', output, (err, reply) => {
 if (err) {
 console.error(`Redis error: ${err}`);
 return;
 }

 console.log(`Output saved to Redis: ${reply}`);
 redisClient.quit();
 });
});
```
In this example, you use the Redis client from the `redis` library to connect to a Redis server. Then you use the `exec` method from the `child_process` module to run the `initdb` command, capturing its output in the `stdout` and `stderr` variables.

You then concatenate the `stdout` and `stderr` variables into a single string, `output`, and use the `set` method from the Redis client to save this string to a Redis key called `initdb_output`.

If the operation was successful, the message "Output saved to Redis: OK" will be logged. Otherwise, an error message will be logged. Finally, the Redis connection is closed using the `quit` method.

Here's an example of how you could create a web service that allows users to allocate and manage PostgreSQL clusters:


```javascript
const express = require('express');
const { exec } = require('child\_process');
const redis = require('redis');

const app = express();
const redisClient = redis.createClient();

app.use(express.json());

app.post('/clusters', (req, res) => {
 const clusterName = req.body.clusterName;
 const dataDirectory = req.body.dataDirectory;

 const cmd = `initdb -D ${dataDirectory}/${clusterName}`;

 exec(cmd, (error, stdout, stderr) => {
 if (error) {
 console.error(`exec error: ${error}`);
 res.status(500).send({ error: error.message });
 return;
 }

 const output = `stdout: ${stdout}\nstderr: ${stderr}`;
 redisClient.hset('clusters', clusterName, output, (err, reply) => {
 if (err) {
 console.error(`Redis error: ${err}`);
 res.status(500).send({ error: err.message });
 return;
 }

 console.log(`Cluster created: ${clusterName}`);
 res.status(201).send({ message: `Cluster created: ${clusterName}` });
 });
 });
});

app.get('/clusters/:clusterName', (req, res) => {
 const clusterName = req.params.clusterName;

 redisClient.hget('clusters', clusterName, (err, reply) => {
 if (err) {
 console.error(`Redis error: ${err}`);
 res.status(500).send({ error: err.message });
 return;
 }

 if (!reply) {
 res.status(404).send({ error: `Cluster not found: ${clusterName}` });
 return;
 }

 console.log(`Cluster found: ${clusterName}`);
 res.send({ clusterName, output: reply });
 });
});

app.delete('/clusters/:clusterName', (req, res) => {
 const clusterName = req.params.clusterName;

 redisClient.hdel('clusters', clusterName, (err, reply) => {
 if (err) {
 console.error(`Redis error: ${err}`);
 res.status(500).send({ error: err.message });
 return;
 }

 if (reply === 0) {
 res.status(404).send({ error: `Cluster not found: ${clusterName}` });
 return;
 }

 console.log(`Cluster deleted: ${clusterName}`);
 res.send({ message: `Cluster deleted: ${clusterName}` });
 });
});

const port = process.env.PORT || 3000;
